<GlossaryTerm id="CDR0000046554"><TermName>radon</TermName><TermPronunciation>(RAY-don)</TermPronunciation><TermDefinition><DefinitionText>A radioactive gas that is released by uranium, a substance found in soil and rock. Breathing in too much radon can damage lung cells and may lead to lung cancer.</DefinitionText><Dictionary>Cancer.gov</Dictionary><Audience>Patient</Audience></TermDefinition><MediaLink ref="CDR0000708942" type="audio/mpeg" alt="Pronunciation of dictionary term &quot;radon&quot;" language="en" id="_3"/><MediaLink ref="CDR0000708941" type="audio/mpeg" alt="Pronunciation of dictionary term &quot;radón&quot;" language="es" id="_4"/><SpanishTermName>radón</SpanishTermName><SpanishTermDefinition><DefinitionText>Gas radiactivo que emana del uranio, una sustancia que se encuentra en el suelo y la roca. Inhalar demasiado radón puede dañar las células de los pulmones y conducir al cáncer de pulmón.</DefinitionText><Dictionary>Cancer.gov</Dictionary><Audience>Patient</Audience></SpanishTermDefinition><DateLastModified>2008-02-04</DateLastModified><RelatedInformation><RelatedExternalRef UseWith="en" xref="http://www.cancer.gov/about-cancer/causes-prevention/risk/substances/radon/radon-fact-sheet">Radon and Cancer</RelatedExternalRef><RelatedExternalRef UseWith="es" xref="http://www.cancer.gov/espanol/cancer/causas-prevencion/riesgo/sustancias/radon/hoja-informativa-radon">Radón y cáncer</RelatedExternalRef></RelatedInformation></GlossaryTerm>
